Dialogue: 0,0:56:25.11,0:56:31.20,Default,,0,0,0,,see me in the headlights. And the nicest\Nsound in the world was those those what
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.20,0:56:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,do you call them? Compression brakes.\Nyou know, the air brakes, you know, all
Dialogue: 0,0:56:35.04,0:56:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,of a sudden I'd hear and I could hear he\Nwas feathering the brakes, you know, to
Dialogue: 0,0:56:40.40,0:56:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,stop on an icy highway with an\N18-wheeler. He's got to start about
Dialogue: 0,0:56:44.40,0:56:48.79,Default,,0,0,0,,quarter mile away\Nand gradually slow down, you know, and
Dialogue: 0,0:56:48.79,0:56:52.64,Default,,0,0,0,,then he'd say, "Hop in, kid." You know,\Nnow I guess it's illegal to pick up
Dialogue: 0,0:56:52.64,0:56:55.92,Default,,0,0,0,,hitchhikers.\NIn those days, they would have a sign.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:55.92,0:56:59.59,Default,,0,0,0,,It said, "It's illegal to pitch up pick\Nup hitchhikers."
Dialogue: 0,0:56:59.59,0:57:04.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And uh they would have a sign illegal to\Npick up hitchhikers. Come on then, kid.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:04.79,0:57:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The mutual trust that everyone had and\Nuh
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.07,0:57:14.24,Default,,0,0,0,,crime was extremely rare during the war.\NCrime just practically never happened.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:14.24,0:57:20.31,Default,,0,0,0,,There was no no crime uh sub\Ncivilization, sub society,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.31,0:57:26.88,Default,,0,0,0,,much less were they glamourage. John\NDillinger was public enemy number one.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.88,0:57:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,told my mother before bed. He escaped\Nsomewhere near Wisconsin and uh yeah, in
Dialogue: 0,0:57:33.11,0:57:37.11,Default,,0,0,0,,fact, he was caught in Wisconsin, right?\NThe hit line was Don Dillinger on the
Dialogue: 0,0:57:37.11,0:57:42.24,Default,,0,0,0,,loose. Jeez, everybody locked our doors\Nat night.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:42.24,0:57:46.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. My father go out and double lock\Nthe garage door so John Dillinger
Dialogue: 0,0:57:46.07,0:57:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,couldn't steal our car and escape\Nour 1929 Hudson or whatever the heck it
Dialogue: 0,0:57:53.11,0:57:58.40,Default,,0,0,0,,was.\N29 modeling Ford Roadster, you know. So,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:58.40,0:58:04.88,Default,,0,0,0,,I just thought I'd amuse you with a few\Nlittle personal vignettes, you know. Uh
Dialogue: 0,0:58:04.88,0:58:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,but I still hold in mind sort of the\Nideal of America as a a unified uh giant
Dialogue: 0,0:58:11.76,0:58:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,family.\NUh
Dialogue: 0,0:58:15.59,0:58:23.83,Default,,0,0,0,,of friendliness and trust and uh\Neverybody was pretty integrous and uh we
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.83,0:58:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,worked our best for the good of the\Ncountry and the war effort and everyone
Dialogue: 0,0:58:27.35,0:58:32.40,Default,,0,0,0,,else.\NSo the goodwill and the trust that
Dialogue: 0,0:58:32.40,0:58:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,prevailed\Nmade it what's now called the great
Dialogue: 0,0:58:36.07,0:58:42.07,Default,,0,0,0,,society you know\Nthere you take war you see war which is
Dialogue: 0,0:58:42.07,0:58:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,supposed to be so awful which it was too\NI mean
Dialogue: 0,0:58:47.68,0:58:54.64,Default,,0,0,0,,yeah and uh but the other side of it was\Nthat it brought a great unification of
Dialogue: 0,0:58:54.64,0:58:59.35,Default,,0,0,0,,the country so the counterbalance of the\Nnegativity of the war was almost off set
Dialogue: 0,0:58:59.35,0:59:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,by the the goodwill of civilization and\Nuh they brought mother from the
Dialogue: 0,0:59:09.20,0:59:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,stove to the factory and uh you know\Nthis was an agrarian society
Dialogue: 0,0:59:16.16,0:59:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,when I grew up 50% of the population\Nlived on the farm
Dialogue: 0,0:59:20.88,0:59:25.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and the work of men and women were\Ndivided as they would be in a rural
Dialogue: 0,0:59:25.59,0:59:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,agrarian society\Nand Nobody thought a woman would go out
Dialogue: 0,0:59:30.00,0:59:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and get a job. If she got a job,\Neverybody would feel sorry for her and
Dialogue: 0,0:59:33.83,0:59:38.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the guy would be would die of shame that\Nhis wife had to work. So it was a
Dialogue: 0,0:59:38.64,0:59:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,totally different society and they\Ndidn't see women's position as inferior.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:43.52,0:59:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,On the contrary,\Nmother was revered and respected and
Dialogue: 0,0:59:48.88,0:59:53.68,Default,,0,0,0,,when a woman entered the room, a man\Nstood up in respect. That was respect.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:53.68,0:59:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,She held he held the door open to the\Ncar out of respect for women.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:58.72,1:00:04.83,Default,,0,0,0,,were revered. So, she was the queen of\Nthe domestic scene.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.35,1:00:09.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And it wasn't them that were dominant at\Nall.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:09.92,1:00:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,George, you're not going to sit at smoke\Nin that room. How? My
Dialogue: 0,1:00:14.40,1:00:18.96,Default,,0,0,0,,grandfather would take his pipe and hide\Nit in his hand. And he'd scurry through
Dialogue: 0,1:00:18.96,1:00:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,the living room like this. And my\Ngrandmother say, "Frank, Frank, the
Dialogue: 0,1:00:22.31,1:00:29.44,Default,,0,0,0,,drapes." And she\NI just wanted to give you a picture how
Dialogue: 0,1:00:29.44,1:00:34.64,Default,,0,0,0,,it really was. And uh so the woman of\Ncourse did the house work because she
Dialogue: 0,1:00:34.64,1:00:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,was raising the kids and the guy of\Ncourse did the work out in the farm in
Dialogue: 0,1:00:39.59,1:00:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the field. It was very heavy duty work\Nand they both worked 12 hours a day and
Dialogue: 0,1:00:45.20,1:00:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,then some.\Nthough I say them, you know, they were
Dialogue: 0,1:00:49.11,1:00:53.76,Default,,0,0,0,,equal and uh\Ntrying to depict the woman as inferior
Dialogue: 0,1:00:53.76,1:01:00.31,Default,,0,0,0,,or whatever was sort of a mis mis\Nmis miscasting it. It's isn't the way it
Dialogue: 0,1:01:00.31,1:01:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,was.\NMother ruled the household with an iron
Dialogue: 0,1:01:03.76,1:01:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,hand and uh in the ultimate, you know,\Nuh if one of them had to make the
Dialogue: 0,1:01:10.07,1:01:15.92,Default,,0,0,0,,decision, the man had to. It was\Nexpected that he would do it. you know
Dialogue: 0,1:01:15.92,1:01:20.64,Default,,0,0,0,,whether a certain\Nsick animal was enough to be put down or
Dialogue: 0,1:01:20.64,1:01:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,not.\NHe'd say, "Yeah, you you have to
Dialogue: 0,1:01:24.88,1:01:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,decide."\NSo he got the tough decisions. And
Dialogue: 0,1:01:31.92,1:01:35.83,Default,,0,0,0,,so that to me is what a normal society\Nis, where everybody's equal no matter
Dialogue: 0,1:01:35.83,1:01:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,what they're doing. One was not\Nconsidered better than the other at all.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:40.96,1:01:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,They were very equal. No family could\Nlive without the mother. That was for
Dialogue: 0,1:01:45.35,1:01:51.52,Default,,0,0,0,,sure. Four kids in a farm.\NWithout a mother, you'd never make it.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:51.52,1:01:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,She worked 12 hours a day canning and\Npeeling.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:55.28,1:02:00.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And uh\Nthe reverence for life that is revealed
Dialogue: 0,1:02:00.31,1:02:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,by that kind of a life style, you know,\Nis what I sort of hold as an ideal for
Dialogue: 0,1:02:06.40,1:02:14.16,Default,,0,0,0,,society. Unification and oneness,\Ncommitment to everybody.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:14.16,1:02:16.79,Default,,0,0,0,,You could go out in the street if you\Nneeded to ride. Stick your thumb out.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:16.79,1:02:21.35,Default,,0,0,0,,You usually got rides like that. First\Ncar or two would stop and get you.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.35,1:02:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Nobody's left standing out on the street\Nby themselves. Very interesting kind of
Dialogue: 0,1:02:25.20,1:02:30.48,Default,,0,0,0,,society to live in.\NYeah. And benevolence was left up to the
Dialogue: 0,1:02:30.48,1:02:36.31,Default,,0,0,0,,churches and benevolent societies\Nand the government wasn't involved in
Dialogue: 0,1:02:36.31,1:02:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,it. You see, so\Nreligion served a different function.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:41.44,1:02:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And it was the backbone of benevolence\Nand the churches you know
Dialogue: 0,1:02:52.00,1:02:57.59,Default,,0,0,0,,established all the hospitals all around\Nthem and the charity clinics etc.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:57.59,1:03:02.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the world I grew up all every\Ndoctor donated a certain amount of time
Dialogue: 0,1:03:02.24,1:03:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,to the hospital which had a clinic. So\Npeople didn't have money, they went to
Dialogue: 0,1:03:07.28,1:03:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,the clinic and uh the residents and the\Ninterns took care of them and if you had
Dialogue: 0,1:03:12.16,1:03:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,a complicated case, you called the\Nspecialist. So when I was in obstetrics,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:15.59,1:03:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,I delivered maybe 100 kids and uh but if\Nyou got a breach or something difficult
Dialogue: 0,1:03:21.83,1:03:28.40,Default,,0,0,0,,looking twins or a breach or something,\Nyou call the obstatrician. So
Dialogue: 0,1:03:28.40,1:03:32.24,Default,,0,0,0,,the charity patient for nothing had the\Nmost expensive obstitrician in town
Dialogue: 0,1:03:32.24,1:03:38.07,Default,,0,0,0,,attending to her\Nand uh the society sort of evened out in
Dialogue: 0,1:03:38.07,1:03:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,a certain fairness and uh\Nit was free of uh you know distortions
Dialogue: 0,1:03:46.16,1:03:50.79,Default,,0,0,0,,of viewpoint. Nowadays everything is\Ndistorted in viewpoint.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:50.79,1:03:54.07,Default,,0,0,0,,One reason I'm doing the book I'm doing\Nis because there's no way to tell the
Dialogue: 0,1:03:54.07,1:04:00.72,Default,,0,0,0,,truth about anything in our society\Nat all and uh so the current book I'm
Dialogue: 0,1:04:00.72,1:04:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,working on hoping to have it out by June\Nis called the crisis of truth. Nobody
Dialogue: 0,1:04:06.24,1:04:12.35,Default,,0,0,0,,knows what the truth is about anything\Nanywhere in our current society.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:13.76,1:04:18.79,Default,,0,0,0,,The typical criminal case it's always\Nwho done it in politics. Nobody knows
Dialogue: 0,1:04:18.79,1:04:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,who's telling the truth. Can't tell\Nwhere the government is telling you the
Dialogue: 0,1:04:22.16,1:04:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,truth. Can't tell where the testimony is\Nthe truth. People who swear by the Bible
Dialogue: 0,1:04:27.35,1:04:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and then lie up and down.\NNobody knows the truth about anything.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:33.35,1:04:36.88,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like a crisis of truth. And if you\Nwatch every night's news, you'll notice
Dialogue: 0,1:04:36.88,1:04:42.55,Default,,0,0,0,,the whole focus is always on what is the\Ntruth of the matter.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:42.55,1:04:46.96,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, our relationship with the\NMiddle East and al-Qaeda and the whole
Dialogue: 0,1:04:46.96,1:04:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,thing. What is the truth? So they\Nfinally captured this guy in the spider
Dialogue: 0,1:04:50.88,1:04:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,hole\Nand people what truth is he speaking so
Dialogue: 0,1:04:55.83,1:05:00.28,Default,,0,0,0,,far I don't think he's spoken any\Nlikely.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:02.64,1:05:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So we have a society\Nin which nobody knows what the truth is
Dialogue: 0,1:05:07.52,1:05:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,nor does anybody know how to define what\Nthe truth is
Dialogue: 0,1:05:11.35,1:05:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,and if they could define it how they\Nwould ascertain it anyway. So it seemed
Dialogue: 0,1:05:16.64,1:05:20.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to me\Nbecause that's what the world. So I was
Dialogue: 0,1:05:20.07,1:05:23.68,Default,,0,0,0,,going to write a different book, but I\Nsubstituted this one. It seemed I moved
Dialogue: 0,1:05:23.68,1:05:28.07,Default,,0,0,0,,this one up because\Ncrisis of truth. Nobody knows what the
Dialogue: 0,1:05:28.07,1:05:32.31,Default,,0,0,0,,truth is about anything much less God or\Nspirituality.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:32.31,1:05:36.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And now we have secularization. There's\Na movement
Dialogue: 0,1:05:36.40,1:05:43.68,Default,,0,0,0,,based on all kinds of sophistries.\NAnd so the the only real source of truth
Dialogue: 0,1:05:43.68,1:05:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,is going to be removed altogether\Nsecularized. So the
Dialogue: 0,1:05:49.92,1:05:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,we'll fall back into sophistry.\NI thought the difficulties of sophistry
Dialogue: 0,1:05:57.03,1:06:05.76,Default,,0,0,0,,were solved back about 400 BC\Nin the Greek civilization. Sophus
Dialogue: 0,1:06:05.76,1:06:12.96,Default,,0,0,0,,uh taught how to shade the truth so as\Nto accomplish success in the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:12.96,1:06:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Sophus for a fee would teach students\Nhow to be prominent in public life and
Dialogue: 0,1:06:19.83,1:06:26.07,Default,,0,0,0,,how to shade the truth by nuances.\NAnd that's become of course
Dialogue: 0,1:06:26.07,1:06:31.03,Default,,0,0,0,,uh the common genre of communication\Nnowadays. Everybody has to shade the
Dialogue: 0,1:06:31.03,1:06:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,truth with a little innuendo.\NAnd of course the way the media do it is
Dialogue: 0,1:06:36.24,1:06:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,if they favor one position they see TV\Ntime TV exposure even a split second is
Dialogue: 0,1:06:42.96,1:06:48.55,Default,,0,0,0,,worth a million right. So they you have\Nthe com the camera hesitate just a split
Dialogue: 0,1:06:48.55,1:06:53.03,Default,,0,0,0,,second longer on this picture rather\Nthan this picture and now people are
Dialogue: 0,1:06:53.03,1:07:00.48,Default,,0,0,0,,programmed through this picture. So on\Ntop of all the untruth, you now have the
Dialogue: 0,1:07:00.48,1:07:04.96,Default,,0,0,0,,almost organized programming via the\Nmedia and therefore the slant of the
Dialogue: 0,1:07:04.96,1:07:08.40,Default,,0,0,0,,media.\NWhich news channel calibrates higher
Dialogue: 0,1:07:08.40,1:07:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,than another, etc. So I thought\NI probably should wait until I get some
Dialogue: 0,1:07:14.48,1:07:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,fatal disease and then publish it. But\NI figured that's cowardice
Dialogue: 0,1:07:22.31,1:07:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,and\NI just soon be shot down walking is
Dialogue: 0,1:07:26.64,1:07:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,laying down. So\Nnaturally you can't tell the truth about
Dialogue: 0,1:07:33.44,1:07:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,everything. Can you imagine the\Ndevastation to the world if you tell the
Dialogue: 0,1:07:37.44,1:07:43.72,Default,,0,0,0,,truth about everything?\NLord, are you sure?
Dialogue: 0,1:07:45.92,1:07:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It is okay for me to publish this book\Nsoon.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:50.40,1:08:00.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Your witness.\NWe'll only leave a few things out.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:02.55,1:08:07.68,Default,,0,0,0,,There are organizations known for\Nintimidation by litigation. So, we won't
Dialogue: 0,1:08:07.68,1:08:11.68,Default,,0,0,0,,ref we won't mention them. We'll give\Nthe name of the org and then we'll say
Dialogue: 0,1:08:11.68,1:08:16.79,Default,,0,0,0,,we'll leave the calibration blank and\Nwe'll say due to conditions over which
Dialogue: 0,1:08:16.79,1:08:20.08,Default,,0,0,0,,we have no control. We've been advised\Nto leave this calibration out of the
Dialogue: 0,1:08:20.08,1:08:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,book.\NThe only trouble is I'm sure we get sued
Dialogue: 0,1:08:24.79,1:08:30.08,Default,,0,0,0,,for that because by inference I have\Ndefamed them. You see what I'm saying?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:30.08,1:08:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So here we have a free society. You're\Nallowed to say anything you want.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:33.52,1:08:36.79,Default,,0,0,0,,However, you're probably going to get\Nsued for it
Dialogue: 0,1:08:36.79,1:08:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,unless it's a lie.\NBecause maligning people's character can
Dialogue: 0,1:08:44.79,1:08:51.15,Default,,0,0,0,,be done freely and there's no recourse.\NIt's free called free speech.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:51.60,1:08:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So this is a society of such complex\Nof complexity now complexity political
Dialogue: 0,1:08:59.44,1:09:04.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and legal balances and nuances that it's\Nvery difficult to
Dialogue: 0,1:09:04.88,1:09:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,really be who you are.\Nyou have freedom of speech, but you'll
Dialogue: 0,1:09:09.75,1:09:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,be sued if you exercise it. So,\Nuh,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:17.60,1:09:24.12,Default,,0,0,0,,so I thought it's a timely time to\Npublish such a book and, uh,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:24.88,1:09:30.64,Default,,0,0,0,,critical to the world's thinking.\NAnd people say things publicly, they're
Dialogue: 0,1:09:30.64,1:09:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,so outrageously facious, you wonder how\Nthey got the courage to say them in
Dialogue: 0,1:09:35.35,1:09:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,public.\NBecause when you calibrate them, they
Dialogue: 0,1:09:38.40,1:09:42.15,Default,,0,0,0,,come out like 140 or something, you\Nknow, and you say, "How could a person
Dialogue: 0,1:09:42.15,1:09:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,who's\Nrunning for the presidency make a
Dialogue: 0,1:09:46.40,1:09:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,statement that cal 140 or 150?"\NOh god.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:53.75,1:10:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what we're going to do. And uh\Nif it's our last section on the planet,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:00.00,1:10:07.67,Default,,0,0,0,,so be it.\NSo that'll be fun. That'll be fun to
Dialogue: 0,1:10:07.67,1:10:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,look forward to that one. Of course, the\Nbooks I've done appeal to a very small
Dialogue: 0,1:10:11.52,1:10:16.48,Default,,0,0,0,,audience.\NProbably half of 1% of the world is that
Dialogue: 0,1:10:16.48,1:10:21.36,Default,,0,0,0,,much\Npeople who are seriously spiritually
Dialogue: 0,1:10:21.36,1:10:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,committed are rare as hens.\NAnd you know there's a lot a lot of
Dialogue: 0,1:10:26.00,1:10:30.80,Default,,0,0,0,,people what what percentage of the\Npopulation is really uh sue over the
Dialogue: 0,1:10:30.80,1:10:40.56,Default,,0,0,0,,books I've written already just have to\Nask this over 1% over 3% over 5% or 10%.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:40.56,1:10:47.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow over 8%. 9% whoa 8% I didn't know\Nthat many. All right. The book I'm
Dialogue: 0,1:10:47.92,1:10:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,writing now would appeal to over 25%,\N30%, 25% of the population. So,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:56.23,1:11:03.92,Default,,0,0,0,,what's the matter with the other 75%?\NThey must be dead upstairs, right?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:03.92,1:11:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I've always been obsessed with\Nwhat is the truth about things. And
Dialogue: 0,1:11:08.32,1:11:11.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that's why I like to, you know, when I\Nwas a boy, other kids were playing
Dialogue: 0,1:11:11.44,1:11:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,stickball and baseball and football and\Nthings. And I was reading the great
Dialogue: 0,1:11:15.36,1:11:19.84,Default,,0,0,0,,books of the western world, you know,\Nthe apherisms of uh Marcus Aurelius and
Dialogue: 0,1:11:19.84,1:11:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Plato and Socrates and Aristotle.\NA misspent youth, eh,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:29.92,1:11:36.80,Default,,0,0,0,,a misspent youth. Yeah.\NSo now in writing a certain section of
Dialogue: 0,1:11:36.80,1:11:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the book, I had to sort of recall some\Nof the fine points. What was the
Dialogue: 0,1:11:40.80,1:11:45.12,Default,,0,0,0,,argument of between the Sophus and\NSocrates
Dialogue: 0,1:11:45.12,1:11:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and had that all come down about 4 or\N500 BC?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:49.44,1:11:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh because\Nhere we are a few thousand years later
Dialogue: 0,1:11:54.40,1:11:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and people still haven't gotten the\Npoint of it all. You know, it seems like
